1. A well-designed class should have high cohesion, meaning all its methods contribute directly to a single, well-defined responsibility. 
This reduces coupling, improves maintainability, and increases clarity. The StudentPortalHelper class has low cohesion because it handles 
many unrelated tasks such as GPA calculation, CSV export, email formatting, payments, password checking, and caching. According to Arthur Riel's 
heuristic, a class should capture only one key abstraction. To improve cohesion, it should be refactored into smaller classes like GpaCalculator, 
RosterExporter, EmailFormatter, and PaymentProcessor, each with a single, focused responsibility.

3. The current structure does not support dynamic trim-level changes. Each trim level (Base, Luxury, and Sports) is a subclass of Car, which means a 
car's type is fixed when created. In Java, an object's class cannot change at runtime. To switch trims, making a new object is necessary, which causes 
loss of existing data. To fix this, the design should use composition instead of inheritance. The Car class should have a TrimLevel field 
rather than separate subclasses. The TrimLevel interface can be implemented by classes like BaseTrim, LuxuryTrim, and SportsTrim. The Car class can 
include a setTrimLevel() method to change trims at runtime. This allows trim-level changes without recreating the car.

5. Before this course, I occasionally used AI tools like ChatGPT to help me understand coding concepts, debug small programming errors, and get quick 
explanations of topics I found confusing. During this course, I relied on AI to support my learning—for example, by asking it to explain 
Java concepts in simpler terms, help me structure code, and clarify UML diagrams or object-oriented design principles. These tools helped me learn faster, 
reinforced classroom lessons, and gave me immediate feedback when I was stuck. One major benefit I noticed was how AI could break down complex problems into 
step-by-step explanations, which made coding feel less intimidating. It also helped me check my logic and learn better coding practices. However, I learned 
that AI is not perfect—sometimes its answers needed verification or further testing, especially when dealing with more detailed code implementations. Looking 
ahead, I expect AI to continue shaping how I solve problems both academically and professionally by acting as a research assistant, a coding partner, and a 
brainstorming tool. It will help me think more critically, write cleaner code, and find creative solutions faster.